{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17565787","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17565787"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:32:13+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:32:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18466"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18466","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18466"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.58,0.16,0.12,0.05,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11195"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112297"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11195","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11195"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18466"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94347"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11095"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25969"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25970"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39823"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46037"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112297","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112297"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with two hours of central chest pain radiating to his left arm. He has a history of hypertension and hypercholesterolaemia. His medications include amlodipine and atorvastatin. He is an ex-smoker with a 30 pack-year history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears uncomfortable. His pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 165/95 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. Heart sounds are normal with no added sounds. Chest is clear to auscultation. An ECG is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely ECG diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Left bundle branch block","Bifascicular block","Left anterior fascicular block","Left ventricular hypertrophy","Ventricular paced rhythm"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis ECG shows characteristic features of left bundle branch block (LBBB). \u003Cstrong\u003ELeft bundle branch block\u003C/strong\u003E occurs when there is a delay or block in the conduction of electrical impulses through the left bundle branch. The diagnostic criteria include: QRS duration \u2265120ms, broad monophasic R wave in leads I, aVL, V5, and V6, absence of Q waves in leads I, V5, and V6, dominant S wave in V1, and appropriate discordant ST-T wave changes (ST segment and T wave pointing opposite to the main QRS deflection).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe presence of LBBB makes diagnosis of acute myocardial infarction challenging as the bundle branch block masks typical ST-segment changes. The Sgarbossa criteria can help identify acute MI in the presence of LBBB: concordant ST elevation \u22651mm in leads with a positive QRS complex, concordant ST depression \u22651mm in V1-V3, and excessively discordant ST elevation \u22655mm in leads with a negative QRS complex. The modified Sgarbossa criteria use a ST/S ratio cut-off of \u22650.25 instead of absolute ST elevation. In patients presenting with chest pain and new or presumed new LBBB, this should be treated as a STEMI equivalent requiring urgent reperfusion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBifascicular block\u003C/strong\u003E refers to a combination of right bundle branch block with either left anterior or left posterior fascicular block. The ECG would show features of RBBB (RSR\u0027 pattern in V1) along with left axis deviation (for LAFB) or right axis deviation (for LPFB).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELeft anterior fascicular block\u003C/strong\u003E shows left axis deviation with small Q waves in leads I and aVL, and small R waves in leads II, III, and aVF. The QRS duration is typically normal (\u0026lt;120ms), unlike what is seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELeft ventricular hypertrophy\u003C/strong\u003E can cause QRS widening and ST-T changes, but typically shows increased QRS amplitude in the lateral leads with a \u0027strain\u0027 pattern of ST depression and T wave inversion. The QRS morphology would not show the typical LBBB pattern seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVentricular paced rhythm\u003C/strong\u003E also produces wide QRS complexes but typically shows large spike artifacts preceding each QRS complex and a pattern that more closely resembles LBBB. The absence of pacing spikes rules out this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Left bundle branch block is characterized by QRS duration \u003E120ms, dominant S wave in V1, and broad monophasic R wave in V6.","Secondary ST-T wave changes in LBBB typically show ST elevation and T wave inversion opposite to the main QRS deflection.","Sgarbossa criteria can help identify acute myocardial infarction in the presence of LBBB.","New or presumed new LBBB in the setting of acute chest pain should be treated as STEMI equivalent."],"references":["Life in the Fast Lane. Left bundle branch block (LBBB) \u2013 ECG library diagnosis. Available at: https://litfl.com/left-bundle-branch-block-lbbb-ecg-library","Healio. Left bundle branch block (LBBB) ECG review. Available at: https://www.healio.com/cardiology/learn-the-heart/ecg-review/ecg-topic-reviews-and-criteria/left-bundle-branch-block-lbbb-review","ECG Waves. Left bundle branch block (LBBB): ECG criteria, causes, management. Available at: https://ecgwaves.com/topic/left-bundle-branch-block-lbbb-ecg-criteria-treatment","ECGpedia. LBBB. Available at: https://en.ecgpedia.org/wiki/LBBB","JAMA Cardiology. A revised definition of left bundle branch block using time to notch. Available at: https://jamanetwork.com/journals/jamacardiology/article-abstract/2816973"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94347"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18466"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21372"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21372","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21372"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/GDcURkUxG8d1JXhjA0AhHBbKxkvZb4.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/GDcURkUxG8d1JXhjA0AhHBbKxkvZb4.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":600,"height":355}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94347","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94347"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-28T16:47:23+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-28T16:48:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11195"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112297"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":